BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:event_313251480@meetup.com
SEQUENCE:1
DTSTAMP:20260306T070108Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260306T120000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260306T140000
SUMMARY:The Lakeshore Psychiatric Hospital and Camp M (Special Extended We
 ekday Tour)
DESCRIPTION:Toronto History Walks\n\\*\\***The Toronto History Walks Yearl
 y Pass is available. Get it now for $125.00 for 1 year of unlimited tours\
 , email**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**\n**for more information or fo
 r signing up!\\*\\***\n\n\\*\\* **Please note: Please e-transfer the ticke
 t amount when booking your space for this tour! You can e-transfer to the 
 following email at:**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**\n\nElizabeth Simc
 oe named the area now known as Mimico for the thousands of pigeons that bl
 ackened the sky at the western end of the settlement. Mimico was originall
 y located at the confluence of Mimico Creek and Dundas Street.\n\nWilliam 
 Gamble\, opened a sawmill and built a settlement for the workers nearby. E
 tobicoke's first church\, Christ Church was opened on Church Street which 
 became Royal York Road. Mimico is a walkable neighbourhood and a great pla
 ce to stroll and discover our amazing history.\n\nThe Lakeshore Hospital w
 as built in 1888 as the Mimico Asylum\, its doors opened on January 21\, 1
 889.\n\nThe original idea for the hospital was a series of cottages design
 ed by Doctor Joseph Workman who wanted a resort type feel to the hospital.
  The architect was Kivas Tully\, who worked with gardener Samuel Matheson.
  Most of the buildings were built by the patients themselves\, and helped 
 with laundry duties\, and tended to the vast gardens.\n\nBut a different s
 tory emerged that most Canadians had no idea about. And that was the story
  of Camp M - Mimico.\n\nIn 1887\, the Victoria Industrial School for Boys 
 opened on old Horner Avenue in Mimico\, just blocks from the site of the n
 ew Mimico Hospital for the Insane (Humber College.) The school\, which was
  a juvenile reformatory\, hoped to break the bad boys through moral and ac
 ademic education and old fashioned hard work. I hope there was a positive 
 outcome.\n\nIn 1927\, the school changed its name to the Mimico Reform Sch
 ool. But it was the war years 1939-1945 that really surprised me as a Toro
 ntonian. It was known as Camp M or Internment Camp 22\, the largest camp f
 or POWs in the centre of a large Canadian city.\n\nMost camps were constru
 cted in rural areas\, and the camp provided space for more than 520 German
  nationals. The history of this camp is fascinating and had links to the T
 oronto Central Prison on Strachan Avenue and the Mimico Hospital directly 
 to the south on lakeshore where we begin this tour.\n\nThis walking tour i
 s for all levels and walkers. The tour begins at the New Toronto Public Li
 brary Branch at 110 Eleventh Street just south of Lakeshore. We end this t
 our at Kipling and Horner Avenue\, just a few blocks to the north of the o
 ld hospital!\n\nThis tour has a ticket price of $15.00 per person!\n\n\\*\
 \* **Please note: Please e-transfer the ticket amount when booking your sp
 ace for this tour! You can e-transfer to the following email at:**\n**toro
 ntohistorywalks@gmail.com**
URL;VALUE=URI:https://www.meetup.com/the-history-of-parkdale/events/313251
 480/
STATUS:CONFIRMED
CREATED:20260207T134213Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260207T134213Z
CLASS:PUBLIC
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:event_312785945@meetup.com
SEQUENCE:1
DTSTAMP:20260306T070108Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260307T120000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260307T140000
SUMMARY:Toronto and the Holocaust -5TH ANNUAL EVENT
DESCRIPTION:Toronto History Walks\n\\*\\***The Toronto History Walks Explo
 rer Pass is available. Get it now for $125.00 for 1 year of unlimited tour
 s\, email**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**\n**for more information or 
 for signing up!\\*\\***\n\n\\*\\* **Please note: Please e-transfer the tic
 ket price when booking your space for this tour! You can e-transfer to the
  following email at:**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**\n\nLet's connect
  and truly understand our city! That is the true path to peace!\n\nThis wa
 lk is in honour of **Holocaust Remembrance Day**!\n\nThis tour starts in t
 he old "Ward" on the steps of Old City Hall\, and ends at the Kiever Shul 
 in Kensington Market.\n\nWe will weave our way through Baldwin Village the
  real heart of the Jewish community in Toronto. Most information in books 
 about Toronto's Jewish community tends to forget that Baldwin Village was 
 the epic centre of the migration west out of the "Ward\," and that the wor
 ld famous Baycrest Hospital was established in Baldwin Village.\n\nThe mig
 ration west continued in the early to mid twentieth century\, and the Jewi
 sh residents established the Jewish Market in Kensington Market\, and from
  there to Bathurst and Lawrence area.\n\nA fascinating story of heartbreak
  and heroism amid the horror of war and holocaust. An important walk for u
 s all! A lesson from the past needed today!\n\nAlong the way we will explo
 re the history of the Jewish Community\, The Christie Pits Riot\, the infa
 mous Swastika Club of Woodbine Beach\, The Holocaust\, and Toronto's place
  before\, during and after this sad and tragic historical event. Our tour 
 begins in the mid-19th century\, and ends with the liberation of Europe in
  May of 1945. We will discuss ways to promote this history and how to tack
 le intolerance!\n\nThis is our fifth annual event!\n\nThis walking tour is
  for all walking levels and fitness skills. Please dress for the season an
 d bring water. And remember to bring your love of history as well. Hope to
  see you there.\n\nThis walking tour begins on the steps of Old City Hall 
 and ends in Kensington Market.\n\nThis tour has a ticket price of $15.00 p
 er person.\n\n\\*\\* **Please note: Please e-transfer the ticket price whe
 n booking your space for this tour! You can e-transfer to the following em
 ail at:**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**
URL;VALUE=URI:https://www.meetup.com/the-history-of-parkdale/events/312785
 945/
STATUS:CONFIRMED
CREATED:20260108T155215Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260108T155215Z
CLASS:PUBLIC
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:event_312801209@meetup.com
SEQUENCE:1
DTSTAMP:20260306T070108Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260307T150000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260307T170000
SUMMARY:30 Historic Events that Changed Toronto Forever
DESCRIPTION:Toronto History Walks\n\\*\\***The Toronto History Walks Yearl
 y Pass is available. Get it now for $125.00 for 1 year of unlimited tours\
 , email**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**\n**for more information or fo
 r signing up!\\*\\***\n\n\\*\\* **Please note: Please e-transfer the ticke
 t amount when booking your space for this tour! You can e-transfer to the 
 following email at:**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**\n\nThis city has 
 changed over the last few years. But what were the events that propelled t
 he city in new ways\, new avenues. This tour looks at the events that trul
 y changed the city for good and some say for bad.\n\nBuildings have been e
 rected and others torn down\, but certain happenings in the city changed t
 he path forward forever. And those events were viewed as monumental at the
  time. Today\, we see the outcome of let's say Hurricane Hazel's fury\, th
 e development of our parkland. Or the building of the subway system in 195
 4.\n\nThe first Great Fire\, Christie Pits Riot\, War of 1812\, Constance 
 Hamilton\, Hurricane Hazel\, and the creation of the Toronto Islands\, all
  changed Toronto's destiny. But over time\, those landmark stories have be
 en forgotten. We need to bring them back and highlight them for the next g
 eneration! Let's get started! This tour explores the downtown area in grea
 t detail\, and uncovers the stories that changed our impression of the cit
 y.\n\nThis walking tour begins on the **steps of Old City Hall.** This wal
 k is for all fitness levels. Please dress for the weather\, and bring your
  love of history was well.\n\nThis tour has a ticket price of $15.00 per p
 erson!\n\n\\*\\* **Please note: Please e-transfer the ticket amount when b
 ooking your space for this tour! You can e-transfer to the following email
  at:**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**
URL;VALUE=URI:https://www.meetup.com/the-history-of-parkdale/events/312801
 209/
STATUS:CONFIRMED
CREATED:20260109T132650Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260109T132650Z
CLASS:PUBLIC
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:event_312801456@meetup.com
SEQUENCE:1
DTSTAMP:20260306T070108Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260308T120000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260308T140000
SUMMARY:Humber Bay Shores\, Mimico Creek\, and Air India Memorial!
DESCRIPTION:Toronto History Walks\n\\*\\***The Toronto History Walks Yearl
 y Pass is available. Get it now for $125.00 for 1 year of unlimited tours\
 , email**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**\n**for more information or fo
 r signing up!\\*\\***\n\n\\*\\* **Please note: Please e-transfer the ticke
 t amount when booking your space for this tour! You can e-transfer to the 
 following email at:**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**\n\nOn a warm June
  day in 1985\, Air India flight 182 left Toronto Pearson headed east for M
 ontreal\, London\, and onward to India\, with 329 passengers and crew. The
  flight never reached London. It was destroyed by a suitcase bomb over the
  north Atlantic Ocean off the shores of Ireland\, resulting in one of the 
 most complicated and politically sensitive investigation in recent Canadia
 n history. Since a vast majority of the passengers were Canadians\, this w
 as the worst terrorist attack against Canadians in our history.\n\nThe out
 come divided families and shone a spotlight on wrong doing at all levels h
 ere and abroad. A fascinating story\, but a tragic one for the victims. Th
 is tour looks at the story in detail and the fallout.\n\nThis tour also ex
 amines the history of the Humber Bay Shores\, and the historic Mimico Cree
 k\, or "where the passenger pigeons take flight." The area is a walkers pa
 radise as it follows the shoreline for great picture taking moments as wel
 l.\n\nIf you have not explored Mimico and the Humber shores\, or new to To
 ronto\, this walk is for you.\n\nThe price of this tour is $15.00 per pers
 on!\n\nThis extensive walking tour begins at the Humber Streetcar Loop on 
 Lakeshore Blvd and the Queensway! We end the tour at Mimico Avenue in Mimi
 co Village on Lakeshore Blvd West.\n\n\\*\\* **Please note: Please e-trans
 fer the ticket amount when booking your space for this tour! You can e-tra
 nsfer to the following email at:**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**
URL;VALUE=URI:https://www.meetup.com/the-history-of-parkdale/events/312801
 456/
STATUS:CONFIRMED
CREATED:20260109T133426Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260109T133426Z
CLASS:PUBLIC
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:event_312865304@meetup.com
SEQUENCE:1
DTSTAMP:20260306T070108Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260314T130000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260314T150000
SUMMARY:Historic Little Italy
DESCRIPTION:Toronto History Walks\n\\*\\***The Toronto History Walks Yearl
 y Pass is available. Get it now for $125.00 for 1 year of unlimited tours\
 , email**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**\n**for more information or fo
 r signing up!\\*\\***\n\n\\*\\* **Please note: Please e-transfer the ticke
 t amount when booking your space for this tour! You can e-transfer to the 
 following email at:**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**\n\nItalians arriv
 ed in Toronto during the late 19th century\, and first settled in the old 
 "Ward\," centred at the corner of University Avenue and College Street. Ov
 er the next few years 40\,000 Italians came to Canada between 1914 to 1918
 \, mostly from southern Italy.\n\nMost Italians had moved west of Bathurst
  Street and the College Street area had emerged as the city's Italian encl
 ave. By the 1920s\, the community we know today as Little Italy emerged as
  a cultural and historic jewel in Toronto!\n\nLeaving southern Italy the m
 ajority immigrated to Toronto—increasing from 4\,900 in 1911\, to 9\,000
  in 1921\, or two percent of Toronto's population at the time.\n\nBut it w
 as the massive influx of Italians after the second world war that changed 
 Toronto forever. They brought a cultural revolution to the way Torontonian
 s thought\, interacted socially\, and ate and of course drank coffee. The 
 sidewalk cafe and patio is one of those things that evolved when the Itali
 ans came to town. And coffee is the best part of waking up\, no that's Max
 well House I believe\, oh well\, need I say more! Hope to see you all on t
 his walking adventure!\n\nThis walking tour is for all walking levels and 
 fitness skills. Please dress for the season and bring water. And remember 
 to bring your love of history as well.\n\nThe walking tour begins outside 
 the **Lillian H. Smith** Library on College Street West just east of Spadi
 na. The tour ends at Shaw Street and College Street West.\n\nThis tour has
  a ticket price of $15.00 per person!\n\n\\*\\* **Please note: Please e-tr
 ansfer the ticket amount when booking your space for this tour! You can e-
 transfer to the following email at:**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**
URL;VALUE=URI:https://www.meetup.com/the-history-of-parkdale/events/312865
 304/
STATUS:CONFIRMED
CREATED:20260113T173747Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260113T173747Z
CLASS:PUBLIC
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:event_312865128@meetup.com
SEQUENCE:1
DTSTAMP:20260306T070108Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260315T120000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260315T140000
SUMMARY:Toronto's Great Fires of 1849\, 1871\, 1904 and 1977!
DESCRIPTION:Toronto History Walks\n\\*\\***The Toronto History Walks Explo
 rer Pass is available. Get it now for $125.00 for 1 year of unlimited tour
 s\, email**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**\n**for more information or 
 for signing up!\\*\\***\n\n\\*\\* **Please note: Please e-transfer the tic
 ket price when booking your space for this tour! You can e-transfer to the
  following email at:**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**\n\nThe destructi
 on of Toronto's downtown started on a windy\, cold night in early spring. 
 The above sentence sounds like a mystery novel set in Victorian England. B
 ut things were about to heat up in old hog town on that April evening. As 
 the workday ended at the E&S Currie Neckwear company on Wellington Street 
 at Bay Street\, on April 19\, 1904\, a tiny flicker of light spelled disas
 ter for the entire city.\n\nA police officer on the downtown beat spotted 
 smoke and flames at precisely 8 pm. He headed to the emergency call box on
  King Street at Bay to alert the fire department\, but by then\, the fire 
 had spread to the adjacent buildings. The fire department responded to a f
 iery nightmare as most of Wellington Street was already in flames. Moreove
 r\, the night was turning colder\, and a stiff wind blew in from the north
 . Toronto's second great fire was about to explode out of control.\n\nToro
 nto was well aware of the dangers of fire. In April of 1849\, a small fire
  started in stables near the corner of Jarvis and King Streets and destroy
 ed the old downtown including St. James Church\, and the market. By the ti
 me the fire was out most of the core of the old city was in ashes. Toronto
 \, after the great fire of 1849\, was a different place. The old town was 
 centred around St. James Church\, and the commercial district was then on 
 King Street East. With the great fire and its aftermath\, there was a shif
 t west\, both physically and emotionally\; the central core moved to Yonge
  and King Streets as the city spread. Now the heart of the business distri
 ct was at risk once again. And the stakes were much higher.\n\nThe fire th
 at had started at the E&S Currie Neckwear Company spread quickly along bot
 h sides of Wellington Street\, as far as Yonge Street to the east and York
  Street to the west. But with a stiff wind blowing\, embers touched off ot
 her fires to the south and southeast\, threatening the historic Bank of Mo
 ntreal building at Yonge and Front Streets. Ships docked at the Yonge Stre
 et and Church Street piers were moved to safety\, and documents from the o
 ld customs house were packed up and moved to other venues around the city.
  Some business owners who had managed to get into their businesses removed
  precious documents before the flames engulfed their premises.\n\nFirefigh
 ters held their ground at several points\, putting up fire lines\, includi
 ng Yonge Street just feet west of the old Bank and around the majestic Que
 en's Hotel. Help came in the form of Queen's Hotel guests\, and staff as t
 hey moved from room to room and tore down draperies\, and dampened the woo
 den window sills. Their efforts saved the Queen's Hotel and possibly the r
 est of the downtown\, including the old Union Station south of Front Stree
 t. Had the Queen's Hotel been destroyed\, the rest of the city may have be
 en destroyed as well.\n\nEight hours after the fire was first spotted\, it
  was brought under control. Residents and business owners fled to the down
 town core to watch their lives go up in smoke. Thousands of curious people
  crowded the streets around the burned area. Toronto would have to be rebu
 ilt\, and fire would be tamed through laws and building restrictions. But 
 out of the great fire of 1904\, a new modern city emerged\; one such build
 ing was the new Union Station which was built on the ruins. The city hasn'
 t suffered a great fire like the one in 1904\, but came close to disaster 
 in 1977\, with the Eaton's Annex fire. That fire just about destroyed the 
 new Eaton Centre. Where would we shop\, that is the question of the day? a
 nd let's not forget 1871. And everyone thought Toronto was boring!\n\nThis
  walk is for all fitness levels. Please dress for the weather. This walk b
 egins and ends outside St. James Cathedral at 106 King Street East at Chur
 ch Street.\n\nThis tour has a ticketed price of $15.00 per person!\n\n\\*\
 \* **Please note: Please e-transfer the ticket price when booking your spa
 ce for this tour! You can e-transfer to the following email at:**\n**toron
 tohistorywalks@gmail.com**
URL;VALUE=URI:https://www.meetup.com/the-history-of-parkdale/events/312865
 128/
